		<title>RadixArk Launches with $100M to Power Efficient AI</title>
		<link>https://ventureburn.com/radixark-launches-with-100m-to-power-efficient-ai/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ekemini]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 05 May 2026 19:00:15 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venture Capital]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=200662</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>RadixArk officially launched today with $100 million in funding. The company aims to solve the massive computational and financial drain that occurs when AI models are deployed at scale. The</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/radixark-launches-with-100m-to-power-efficient-ai/" data-wpel-link="internal">RadixArk Launches with $100M to Power Efficient AI</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.radixark.ai/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">RadixArk </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">officially launched today with $100 million in </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/trillium-raises-13m-for-bio-based-acrylonitrile-plant/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">. The company aims to solve the massive computational and financial drain that occurs when AI models are deployed at scale.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The seed round was co-led by Accel and Spark Capital, with heavy participation from industry titans including Nvidia’s NVentures, AMD, and Broadcom CEO Hock Tan. Other notable individual backers include John Schulman (OpenAI co-founder), Soumith Chintala (creator of PyTorch), and Olivier Pomel (CEO of Datadog). The investment values the Palo Alto-based company at $400 million.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Solving the Memory Crisis</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">As AI models like GPT-4 and Llama 3 become more integrated into daily enterprise workflows, the cost of inference has skyrocketed. Current hardware often struggles with memory inefficiency, leading to wasted compute power and high latency.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">RadixArk is commercialising SGLang, an open-source high-speed inference engine originally developed at LMSYS Org (the research collective behind the famous Chatbot Arena). At its core, RadixArk’s technology acts as an intelligent middle layer between AI models and the chips they run on.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_200663" style="width: 490px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200663" class="size-full wp-image-200663" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/RadixArk_logo.jpg" alt="RadixArk logo" width="480" height="101" /><p id="caption-attachment-200663" class="wp-caption-text">Source: RadixArk</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;We are treating inference, training, and post-training as first-class citizens,&#8221; said Ying Sheng, CEO and co-founder of RadixArk. Sheng, a former engineer at Elon Musk&#8217;s xAI, founded the company alongside Banghua Zhu. &#8220;Our goal is to build an end-to-end infrastructure that gives developers more speed and control without the current overhead.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/trillium-raises-13m-for-bio-based-acrylonitrile-plant/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Trillium Raises $13M for Bio-Based Acrylonitrile Plant</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Kitchen Prep of AI</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">One of the company’s primary innovations is its use of a Radix tree filing system to manage the &#8220;KV cache&#8221;, a type of short-term memory for AI.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To visualise this, think of a professional restaurant kitchen. Instead of chopping onions for every single order, the kitchen preps them in bulk. RadixArk’s software scans incoming queries to see if they share a common beginning (like a long legal document or a specific set of system instructions). If they do, the software skips the redundant processing, reusing the prepped data to generate answers significantly faster and cheaper.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The engine reportedly already serves trillions of tokens per day for early enterprise users who require high-throughput, self-hosted AI deployments.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Strategic Backing</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The involvement of both Nvidia and AMD in the round underscores a rare industry consensus: hardware alone cannot solve the AI scaling problem. Software-level efficiency is now seen as the key to making AI economically viable for the long term.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;The demand for AI compute is infinite, but the physical supply of chips is not,&#8221; noted a spokesperson from Accel. &#8220;RadixArk is essentially expanding the capacity of existing hardware by making every cycle count.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">With the new capital, RadixArk plans to expand its team of systems researchers and scale its managed infrastructure. Beyond inference, the company is already moving into reinforcement learning with its recently released framework, Miles, signalling its intent to become the primary backbone for the next generation of efficient-first AI models.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/radixark-launches-with-100m-to-power-efficient-ai/" data-wpel-link="internal">RadixArk Launches with $100M to Power Efficient AI</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
