					<description><![CDATA[<p>Cytospire Therapeutics has completed a £61 million ($83 million) Series A funding round. The capital will be used to advance Cytospire&#8217;s innovative &#8220;pan-gamma delta&#8221; T-cell engager platform into first-in-man clinical</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/cytospire-secures-61m-series-a-to-advance-cancer-drugs/" data-wpel-link="internal">Cytospire Secures £61M Series A to Advance Cancer Drugs</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.cytospire.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Cytospire Therapeutics</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> has completed a £61 million ($83 million) Series A </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/trillium-raises-13m-for-bio-based-acrylonitrile-plant/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round. The capital will be used to advance Cytospire&#8217;s innovative &#8220;pan-gamma delta&#8221; T-cell engager platform into first-in-man clinical trials in a selection of highly challenging solid tumours.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The round was led by 4BIO Capital, a specialist venture fund focused on advanced therapies. The syndicate brought together a strong set of new and existing investors, including Servier Ventures, the British Business Bank, Sound Bioventures and Criteria Bio Ventures. Existing investors Abingworth and LifeArc Ventures also contributed, demonstrating ongoing belief in the startup&#8217;s scientific merits.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Solving the Toxicity Wall in Cancer Treatment</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Cytospire’s focus is seeking to overcome the shortcomings of first-generation T-cell engagers (TCEs). While traditional TCEs have shown remarkable success in treating liquid cancers like leukaemia, they often hit a toxicity wall when applied to solid tumours. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Since CD3 is found on all T-cells, these treatments cause long-term systemic T-cell over-activation of the immune system, with often toxic side effects such as cytokine release syndrome (CRS) or destruction of non-tumoural tissue. </span><span style="font-weight: 400">The therapeutic nature of Cytospire&#8217;s approach is based on the use of gamma delta T-cells. These are a specialised collection of immune cells that form a direct link between the natural and specific immune response. They are unique in that.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_200659" style="width: 610px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200659" class="size-full wp-image-200659" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Cytospire-Therapeutics.png" alt="Cytospire Therapeutics" width="600" height="61" /><p id="caption-attachment-200659" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Cytospire Therapeutics</p></div>
<p>&#8220;By engaging gamma delta T-cells, we can target cancer antigens previously too toxic for standard immunotherapy,&#8221; said Natalie Mount, CEO of Cytospire. Mount previously led Adaptate Biotherapeutics and GammaDelta Therapeutics, both acquired by Takeda.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/trillium-raises-13m-for-bio-based-acrylonitrile-plant/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Trillium Raises $13M for Bio-Based Acrylonitrile Plant</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Lead Candidate: CYT X300</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">A substantial portion of the £61 million will fund the clinical advancement of CYT X300, Cytospire’s lead therapeutic candidate. </span>CYT X300 is a multispecific antibody targeting EGFR-positive solid tumours, including colorectal, head and neck, and lung cancers.</p>
<p>Preclinical data in non-human primates show CYT X300 is well tolerated, avoiding cytokine storm and serious toxicities seen with other EGFR-targeted CD3 engagers. The company is currently wrapping up IND-enabling studies and GMP manufacturing for CYTX300 and is preparing for phase 1 trials.</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Strategic Growth and the UK Biotech Recovery</span></h2>
<p>Industry analysts see this Series A round as a sign of broader UK biotech investment recovery. The British Business Bank&#8217;s £12 million contribution reflects a strategic interest in retaining high-potential UK life science companies.</p>
<p>&#8220;Our investment in Cytospire provides crucial capital to maintain the UK&#8217;s global edge in complex biologics,&#8221; noted Charlotte Lawrence, British Business Bank. Cytospire&#8217;s pan-gamma delta approach targets multiple immune cell subtypes — delta 1, 2, and 3 — in blood and tumour microenvironments.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/cytospire-secures-61m-series-a-to-advance-cancer-drugs/" data-wpel-link="internal">Cytospire Secures £61M Series A to Advance Cancer Drugs</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
