					<description><![CDATA[<p>Trillium Renewable Chemicals announced that it has closed a $13 million Series B funding round. The additional funding will go to fund the final construction and start-up of &#8220;Project Falcon&#8221;,</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/trillium-raises-13m-for-bio-based-acrylonitrile-plant/" data-wpel-link="internal">Trillium Raises $13M for Bio-Based Acrylonitrile Plant</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.trilliumchemicals.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Trillium Renewable Chemicals</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> announced that it has closed a $13 million Series B </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/deepinfra-raises-107m-inference-infrastructure/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round. The additional funding will go to fund the final construction and start-up of &#8220;Project Falcon&#8221;, the world&#8217;s first demonstration-scale plant to produce 100% bio-based acrylonitrile.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The most recent round of funding was led by HS Hyosung Advanced Materials, a global leader in high-performance carbon fiber, with ongoing support from Capricorn Partners. Adding to the Series A funding of $10.6 million and a $2.5 million non-dilutive US Department of Energy grant received by the company, the round has pushed Trillium&#8217;s total capital raised above $26 million.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Bridging the Gap: From Pilot to Industrial Scale</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Acrylonitrile is a foundational chemical intermediate used to manufacture a staggering array of modern essentials, from high-strength carbon fiber for aerospace to ABS plastics for consumer electronics and nitrile rubber for medical gloves. Until recently, most of the 6 million metric tonne annual market has come from fossil fuel-derived propylene.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_200645" style="width: 410px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200645" class="wp-image-200645" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Trillium.png" alt="Trillium logo" width="400" height="120" /><p id="caption-attachment-200645" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Trillium</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Trillium wants to shake things up, however, by using a confidential thermochemical technique that transforms plant-derived glycerol (a biodiesel and soap production waste stream) into &#8220;drop-in&#8221; acrylonitrile, a chemical whose chemical composition is entirely indistinguishable from that derived from petroleum.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">“We are now moving from technical proof to commercial proof,” said Corey Tyree, CEO of Trillium Renewable Chemicals. “This funding allows us to demonstrate that bio-based acrylonitrile can meet industrial performance standards at meaningful production volumes. Project Falcon is the bridge that takes our technology out of the lab and into the global market.”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News:</span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/deepinfra-raises-107m-inference-infrastructure/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400"> DeepInfra Raises $107M To Scale Global Inference Infrastructure</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Strategic Partnership at Port Lavaca</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The demonstration plant (Project Falcon) has been built at INEOS Nitriles&#8217; Green Lake site, Port Lavaca, Texas. </span>INEOS, the world&#8217;s largest acrylonitrile producer, was carefully selected for its existing infrastructure and safety systems. Construction of the facility is complete, marking Trillium&#8217;s first industrial-scale glycerol-to-acrylonitrile deployment. Commissioning begins in Q2 2026, with bio-based product shipments expected to reach customers later this year.</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Decarbonizing the Value Chain</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The environmental stakes are high. By replacing propylene with renewable glycerol, Trillium’s process significantly reduces the carbon footprint of acrylonitrile production. </span>This is attractive to lead investor HS Hyosung, which consumes vast amounts of acrylonitrile for carbon fiber production. Carbon fiber is used in the automotive and hydrogen storage sectors.</p>
<p>&#8220;Accessing sustainable acrylonitrile is an important milestone for the entire industry,&#8221; noted Young-Joon Lee. Lee is Senior Vice President of HS Hyosung Advanced Materials. &#8220;Project Falcon will prove that bio-based chemicals can be scaled to produce a viable alternative.&#8221;</p>
<p>The alternative will be competitive and sustainable, replacing fossil-based products. <span style="font-weight: 400">As the plant begins operations, Trillium is already looking toward the horizon. The company confirmed that a portion of the Series B funds will support the advanced-stage engineering and design of its first full-scale commercial plant, which will represent a tenfold increase in production capacity over Project Falcon</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/trillium-raises-13m-for-bio-based-acrylonitrile-plant/" data-wpel-link="internal">Trillium Raises $13M for Bio-Based Acrylonitrile Plant</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
