					<description><![CDATA[<p>QuantWare, the largest provider of large-scale quantum processors (QPUs), announced an oversubscribed Series B round of $178M (€152M) in financing. This investment was led by Intel Capital, In-Q-Tel (IQT) and</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/quantware-raises-178m-series-b-for-quantum-chips/" data-wpel-link="internal">QuantWare Raises $178M Series B for Quantum Chips</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.quantware.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">QuantWare</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">, the largest provider of large-scale quantum processors (QPUs), announced an oversubscribed Series B round of $178M (€152M) in </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/deepinfra-raises-107m-inference-infrastructure/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">financing</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">.</span></p>
<p>This investment was led by Intel Capital, In-Q-Tel (IQT) and ETF Partners. It was one of the largest private funding rounds in the history of the quantum sector. Investors new and old significantly participated in the round. Including FORWARD.One, Invest, NL Deep Tech Fund, Innovation Quarter and Graduate Ventures.</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The &#8220;TSMC of Quantum&#8221;</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Often referred to as the &#8220;TSMC of quantum computing&#8221;, QuantWare does not build full-stack quantum computers. Instead, it serves as a pure-play foundry and chip designer, providing the specialized hardware that other companies need to build their own systems.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This capital injection arrives alongside the debut of VIO-40K&#x2122;, a revolutionary 3D quantum processor architecture. </span>While the industry has struggled to scale past the 100-qubit threshold, the VIO-40K architecture supports up to 10,000 superconducting qubits. This represents a 100x leap over current state-of-the-art designs, accelerating the timeline for &#8220;quantum advantage&#8221;.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/deepinfra-raises-107m-inference-infrastructure/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">DeepInfra Raises $107M To Scale Global Inference Infrastructure</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Building the &#8220;KiloFab&#8221;</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The centrepiece of QuantWare’s expansion strategy is the construction of KiloFab, a dedicated, industrial-scale fabrication facility located in Delft. The new funding will be used to bring this facility online, increasing the company&#8217;s production capacity by 20x.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_200640" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200640" class="wp-image-200640 size-large" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Diagram-of-a-cube-1024x606.jpg" alt="Diagram of a cube" width="1024" height="606" /><p id="caption-attachment-200640" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">“The promise of quantum computing can only be realized once it can be manufactured and deployed at scale,” said Matt Rijlaarsdam, CEO and co-founder of QuantWare. “VIO-40K delivers the architecture, and KiloFab gives us the industrial muscle to meet global demand. We are moving from a world of laboratory experiments to a world of industrial compute.”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">KiloFab will allow QuantWare to offer &#8220;off-the-shelf&#8221; processors to a global clientele that already includes over 50 customers across 20 countries, ranging from national laboratories to private tech giants.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Strategic Geopolitics and Industry Backing</span></h2>
<p>The participation of Intel Capital and In-Q-Tel underscores the strategic importance of QuantWare’s technology. As Europe, the U.S., and China race to establish dominance, QuantWare’s open-architecture model provides a critical &#8220;neutral&#8221; supply chain layer.</p>
<p>“In superconducting quantum computing, scale is constrained by routing and manufacturability rather than qubit design,” noted Kike Miralles. “QuantWare recognized this bottleneck early. Their ability to deliver high-density, scalable chips makes them the foundation upon which the future of the industry will be built.”</p>
<p>With $178 million in fresh capital and a path toward the 10,000-qubit milestone, QuantWare is positioned to transition the industry into a new age of high-performance, industrial-grade computation.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/quantware-raises-178m-series-b-for-quantum-chips/" data-wpel-link="internal">QuantWare Raises $178M Series B for Quantum Chips</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
